<font color="#FF0000">THE BOBBY GARWOOD STORY</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 26  3:12:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I've just read the newly published &quot;Spite House, the last secret of the Vietnam war&quot; by Monika Jensen-Stevenson. ISBN 0-393-04041-0, and it leaves me feeling that everybody who was alive during the Vietnam era in the US should read it. The author was once a producer with the CBS 60 Minutes show. The book is the story of Bobby Garwood, the marine accused of desertion and the man who was a Marine Lt. Colonel that was tasked with having him assasinated. There are 371 pages in this book. It sells for $20 at amazon.com.<br><br>
How the author got her information on all the super secret hunter-killer and MACSOG operations is one of the questions left to the reader as is the nagging question of what were those men on the Cambodian border doing or what did they know and why did the CIA have them assasinated by Army and Marine special killer teams (that served a 90 day tour)  that got paid for the &quot;hit&quot;. Alot of questions are answered, but I was left with a lot of unanswered questions that I think every citizen or veteran will also be left with and be very troubled by. There are some plain errors in the book, it's not perfect, but they seem to be few.<br><br>
If just some of the Inteligence communities activities in Vietnam are being shown the light of day here and the book is true then I hope everyone has a chance to read this book.
<p><code>--   (mercer) </code><p>


